Is there anybody else tired of seeing moms beat themselves up because their child isn’t potty trained yet? Or are you the mom beating yourself up because your child isn’t potty trained yet?

To be completely honest with you, it could very well be because of any one of the three reasons listed.

1. You’re not consistent: that’s literally the message. The “training” part was for me. Not for my child. Ask yourself, am I setting up an environment for success? And am I doing it consistently?
2. You’re constantly comparing your kids to others. Pressure doesn’t do anything except burst pipes. Pressuring, bribing, or forcing your kids to use the potty when they’re “not” ready will move y’all further from the goal.
3. You’re letting “experts” tell you more about your child than you. Sometimes it takes quieting the noise and planning to execute rather than watching and wishing for your child to magically learn.

If you’ve already passed this stage, at what age did your child learn to potty train? Answer below and watch us all have a different answer 🫶🏽

Ok so hear me out….

I used cloth diapers from birth with both of my kids, and just in the last 2 months of using disposables…i have had less than good experiences.

Yes the “convenience” is nice but have you ever been down to ONE diaper? That’s such an inconvenience having to run out to buy a box. Not to mention, cloth diapers never had shit all up my kids’ back where I needed to use multiple wipes! 

So why did I switch?

Well we used the same diapers for 4 years between both kids (which is a beautiful benefit) but when we moved to this apartment (a much smaller place than our last) I tried to make life easier without the wash load and i threw them all away 😭 

I’m not planning on having a newborn this year so i also didn’t want to “hold on to them just in case”

So now I’m here still changing shit and having to buy diapers 🙄 Potty Training has been in full effect.

If you’ve ever considered using cloth diapers or wanted to start with your new baby because you’d like to reduce cost, waste and excessive trips to target…

DM me “cloth” so i can send you the link for my Beginner’s Guide to Cloth Diapers

3 reasons I meditate with my kids!

1. They get to see me taking care of myself and in turn they want to do it too (leading by example)

2. It teaches them how to regulate their emotions by focusing on their breath (less reactions and more focus)

3. We get to connect on a deeper level and it brings us closer together (family bonding)

It started out with me being overwhelmed and going outside or in a corner to “take time for myself” but every time I’d try to leave, I’d get a response “but i want to come and do it too”

Well if you can’t beat ‘em, join em. So now they’re part of my practice ever so often. I know in this video it’s just Sage, but all 3 of us be out here taking our deep breaths ok. 

Because if it’s one thing i know for sure, these kids need an outlet to unplug and reset too. #avulnerablemom

Some days the kids wake up and choose violence and other days they, (well Sage), chooses yoga

This was a result of a “prepared environment”. He woke up and saw the mat out on the rug (because I had just finished my morning stretch) and their “Morning Yoga” book was left out on the table

So when he woke up, he naturally gravitated to what his environment created for him.

As adults AND children, we have the opportunity to make our own choices; but often times, those choices are really based off of what society presents to us. So until we learn to quiet all the noise around us, we will continuously be choosing what someone else wants for us instead of what we might want for ourselves.

How can you prepare your environment to make different or better choices?

It’s Black Maternal Health Week! #BMHW23 We’re talking about RESTORING JOY as it pertains to the black birthing experience. 

What does that look like? How can we do our part to make sure that all families have the right to birth in a safe and encouraging environment? Who is really supporting and advocating for us, when we sometimes feel like we don’t have the voice to advocate for ourselves.

It’s beautiful to see platforms like @blackmamasmatter & @4kira4moms spread awareness and create movements and alliances around the black maternal mortality rate.

To this day, over 90% of birthing people will choose a hospital birth and honestly i think the conversation should start on where we decide to birth our babies.

Both traumatic birth stories AND positive birth stories hold the weight of the next generation. The power lies in our choices. Let’s continue to share our stories. They need to be heard.

Save & Share ✨

Birth shouldn’t be feared.

The most powerful — and effective — birth affirmations are ones that empower you and rewrite the script in your subconscious mind.

Whatever path your birth takes, be ready

It’s one thing to know that you’re good at something and then there’s moments in reality when you’re tested and you feel as though you know nothing.

I’ve been going through this situation lately where I know what it is I want to show up online and share, but then fear kept me from showing up at all. 

I'm talking about parenting.

With all the information, resources and expert opinions out there, it’s so easy for us to feel like we should be doing this or not doing that when it comes to our kids. We look at our parenting through the eyes of curated content and lectures of how to handle tantrums or misbehavior, but when you’re faced with a parenting struggle, you have no clue how to handle it because it wasn’t actually modeled for you. 

So what do you do instead? You get triggered, you get impatient and you react in ways that force you to apologize later. And while we compare our kids to well behaved Johnny, Johnny’s mama is over there feeling like she ain’t doing enough compared to ____’s kid.

This shit is hard ok!!!! But guess what, we can do hard things. Our children chose us for a reason and I think it’s important to remember that you are not supposed to be perfect. Who the hell is?

BUT, often times the discipline methods we use don’t necessarily help us achieve what it is we really want for our children. 

So i want to help

Here is the facing the fear part: This Sunday, Aug 20th, I will be hosting my very first virtual parenting class. The goal is to help you understand that behavior challenges can create wonderful opportunities to teach your children valuable social and life skills. 

So if you’re struggling with tantrums, your kids not listening or you’ve been feeling annoyed, challenged, or even hurt when it comes to your parenting lately, join me live this Sunday so we can all learn how to be encouraging to our children but most importantly, to ourselves! 

Sign up via the link in my bio!! There’s only 8 spots available, so if you have been waiting for something like this, remember….you think long, you think wrong!

As we close out #blackbreastfeedingweek #bbw23 I just want to say that whether you breastfed for a couple months or a couple years, this journey takes us ALL on a roller coaster of emotions. No matter your experience.

Our bodies are able sustain these little humans around the clock and I want you to know that it does not go unnoticed. The connection and bond that you are creating with your child is something to be proud of.

The day moves a lot faster when we do FOR our kids. Get them dressed, brush their teeth, feed them, bathe them, clean up after them etc

But in the slow moments, when we take time for training and teach them how to do FOR THEMSELVES, we’re honoring their capabilities and instilling the self motivation to learn and contribute.

Talking and telling isn’t teaching….so when I hear moms say out loud that their kids “should know better” because the’ve said ______ a million times….maybe we need to reflect on HOW we’re actually teaching our kids. 

Repetition is key and as a mom we do not need to be adding more things to our plate that we can easily have them do.

They want to help more than we let them……and my message for you today is to ……..LET THEM.

And if they make a mistake, that’s a perfect opportunity for a learning moment. #MotherLikeYouGiveAF

I’ve never been afraid of change and i know that had a lot to do with my upbringing. 

Being born in the 🇻🇮Virgin Islands reminds me that my culture is rooted there but when I had already switched schools 5x by the time i was in 7th grade, the unexpected move to Ohio didn’t seem so different……..until i was actually there.

When we moved to 🇵🇷Puerto Rico, I had no expectations. It wasn’t until I got my first job out of high school that I was forced to “learn their language” and adjust to my surroundings.

I’ve now lived in South Florida longer than ANY place I’ve ever lived, in the longest relationship I’ve ever been in….and that in itself is scary. 

(Although we basically moved every year) some aspect of change, has always been consistent, FOR ME!

I don’t even remember the question the therapist asked me but i said all this to say, this journey is an ongoing process and I’m forcing myself to go backwards in order to move forward. 

I’m uncomfortable when I stay the same, so doing things CONSISTENTLY is not my strength. 

So when I say I’m going to change my life by showing up for myself (online & offline) by being consistent, I have to be the one to believe it. My “Dade County” kids need to know that they’re part of something way bigger.

Play with fire and you just might get burned.🔥🫣

Imma need all my body aware, cycle syncing womben to tap in for me one time.

I recorded this video and uploaded it to my YouTube channel back in July. My cycle had just started so i was excited to possibly track my mood and activities over the course of that cycle….However, the way my body has been set up ALL MY LIFE, it just does what it wants.

This entire year my cycles have gone from 33 days to 49 days to 41, 24, 51, 53 and now I’m 27 days into this one. There’s no consistent pattern, so even trying to predict or prevent fertility, it’s a matter of hope and pray at this point. 

When I conceived with Sage, I was taking clomid/clomiphene over a couple of months, which forced my body to ovulate and when I got pregnant with Baby B…i was still breastfeeding, still with inconsistent cycles so only God knew what happened there.

I’m not trying to conceive, I’m just trying to gain more clarity on MY body so that i can basically be more productive in my day. Like i said I’m a planner at heart so when things don’t align the way that i want it to, instead of beating myself up, i can more so give myself grace because there’s a time and a period for everything.

I’m not asking for anything in particular with this post, just to please share any tips that may help me or any other person that’s reading this when it comes to learning more about your own body.

From activities you do during a certain phase in your cycle, foods you eat or avoid, vitamins you take, etc etc!

Taking time for training and role playing is one of my favorite parenting tip.

Often times as parents we feel as if we’ve said something a million times, over and over again that our kids should know what to do

Cue the infamous saying “they know better”

But do they? 

From cleaning up around the house, washing their bodies, setting boundaries, getting dressed etc…all of these things need constant repetition until they become habits.

If you’re having to constantly repeat yourself for “simple” tasks that your kids should already know, i’m challenging you to think about the process you took to teach them.

showing is better than telling and boundaries is definitely something we have to keep revisiting.

I’m tired y’all cuz now i gotta unpack and I’m still dreading it.

My entire feed/explore page/algorithm is filled with pregnancy announcements, new moms, labor tips and baby bumps all over 🥹. I don’t know what’s in the water but I’m super excited for y’all.

Motherhood is truly the greatest gift I’ve ever experienced and I can only pray that throughout everyone’s pregnancy, you’re also planning intentionally for labor & birth, your feeding choices, postpartum and support.

You don’t have to have a home birth like me or record every single crack and crevice BUT if you’d like witness a positive birth video from beginning to end, comment “BIRTH” and I’ll send you the link with a special discount to my 30 minute birth movie.

My daughter won’t be afraid of birth and my son will know how to provide support. The end.

Big feelings. Little feelings. Happy, Sad, Mad, Frustrated, Disappointed….etc it happens to the best of us.

In Parenting and Parenthood, you WILL go through all the motions and as the adults in the situation, learning how to navigate our own emotions in turn helps them to learn how to handle theirs.

I know my content inspires a lot of you to want to be moms, or become “better” moms….just know that this life is not for the weak!

So next time y’all question why im “exposing” all my kids feelings on this here innanet, know that it’s also helping the mom that is trying to find another alternative to yelling, beating, shaming and blaming. 

With Love, 🫶🏽
